Rating: 4
I found this recipe when it was published in the 2001 Thanksgiving issue of Gourmet. I thought it was a very attractive dessert, so I made it for that Thanksgiving. It turned out very pleasing to both the eye and the palate. I have made many of these since, all just as pretty, and I've never heard a negative comment. I think I've found a new holiday tradition to add to the old standards! I've served this for two Thanksgivings and two Christmases now, and I've given about a dozen as gifts, and they have all turned out beautifully. For gifts, I use an aluminum cake pan for ease (not a pie tin with the slanted sides), and increase the amount of frangipane to fill. For us at home, though, I always use the fluted tart pan with the removeable bottom so it looks just as pretty as can be. I use just barely ripe pears (bosc, anjou...red or green) and if I open the oven and see that the pears haven't lightly browned yet, I leave it in. My old oven is so funky that I never follow the temp/time recommendations in recipes... instead I cook by experience, feel, look. Sometimes the pears are juicier than others so I have needed to dab some pooled liquid off the top of the tart, which I do about 10 minutes before removing from the oven so the frangipane under the liquid has a chance to surface-cook a little. As a ginger lover, I think I'll take a hint from Meg's improvisation, and add a little ginger to the strained apricot preserves... next time... and there will be a next time...

